ELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=G84%2F6668"><gtr:id>D9F5E53F-E19D-460D-9290-A7DCCBF397F5</gtr:id><gtr:title>Development of a neuroelectronic interface for sensing electrical activity in regenerating axons</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>G84/6668</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>We are developing a medical implant for recording electrical signals from nerve fibres (axons) in nerves of the arms and legs. 

The design is based on a bundle of very narrow tubes which is attached to the end of a nerve that has been cut, so that the axons from the nerve regrow through the tubes. The tubes contain electrodes for recording electrical signals in the axons. We have shown that when axons pass through narrow tubes the signals they carry are amplified, making them much easier to detect reliably. Using techniques similar to those used to make microchips, we aim to produce an implant measuring only a few millimetres in diameter that contains a few hundred tubes, each with its own electrodes. 

This device could be used in amputees to connect the nerves in the amputation stump to an artificial limb, in order to bring the prosthesis under the patient?s conscious control. It could also help patients whose nerves have been severed by injury, who often recover poorly even if the nerve is stitched together promptly. Signals recorded from the nerve would trigger muscle stimulators to augment the function of weak or paralysed muscles.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Damage to the nervous system cuts nerve fibres (axons) and often results in permanent disability. The central nervous system has no effective capacity for repair. Although regrowth of axons in peripheral nerves does occur, it is seldom complete and frequently the regrowing axons find their way to the wrong target so that the regenerated nerve ?has its wires crossed?.

This study is a part of a larger programme which aims to produce a device to repair damage to peripheral nerves. This device will serve the dual purpose of encouraging axon regeneration through it and interfacing the regenerating axons to electronic equipment. Signals in axons passing through the device will be sensed and may be used to stimulate muscles and/or control mechanical aids. These aids might be designed to augment function in circumstances where biological recovery through axon regeneration is only partially complete, or they may be intelligent prostheses intended to replace a part of the body which has been lost altogether.

My part of the project concerns the central problem of attaching individual axons to microelectrodes and designing those electrodes so that they can reliably record activity in the axons. This must be done without compromising the long-term survival and function of the axon which is being recorded from. I will explore ways of bringing the exterior surface of axons into intimate and long-lasting physical contact with a microelectrode array by using cell adhesion molecules. Subsequently I will examine the effectiveness of various electrode configurations in order to optimise sensitivity. Finally I will ensure that the materials used are biocompatible by implanting samples under the skin of adult rats and subsequently examining them for any adverse reaction.

The main collaborators are:
Dr E Tarte: Fabrication of microelectrode arrays
Dr R Cameron: Development of biocompatible flexible polymer substrates 
Dr W Huck: Microcontact printing on polymer substrates The earliest practical application of the project as a whole is expected to be its use for interfacing nerves in the arm or leg to intelligent prostheses after limb loss or amputation. In the longer term, the technology developed in my part of the project will underpin work on more complex interfacing problems in the damaged spinal cord and brain.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-08-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2005-09-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>200497</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>5470BFE8-5014-40D3-80E3-5B6C9EB4BFDD</gtr:id><gtr:title>Microchannels as axonal amplifiers.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>IEEE transactions on bio-medical engineering</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/87b763be6e3f33e970b61528a65aea08"><gtr:id>87b763be6e3f33e970b61528a65aea08</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Fitzgerald JJ</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2008-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0018-9294</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>jUop5ditn37</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>AA40549F-B4DC-44B2-B33C-4713BB3D8399</gtr:id><gtr:title>A regenerative microchannel neural interface for recording from and stimulating peripheral axons in vivo.</gtr:title><gtr:parent